2019-03-14

Calibration, calibration, calibration. Like they said at the SNAK workshop. I need to *&$"ing calibrate otherwise my recordings are useless!¶

So, I'm going to try and answer some of the questions I've always wanted to :¶

1) Do speaker playbacks show variation over time?¶

2) How similar are the SMPs to each other?¶

3) How similar are the SANKENs to each other?¶

What was done:¶

I set up the microphones on an L-shaped azimuthal swivel aligned to the Vifa speaker (soldered 8/2/2018, used through the 2018 field season). The azimuthal swivel ensures that the mic remains at a fixed radial distance to the speaker, and only the direction of arrival of the speaker playback changes. Here is a very bad hand drawn schematic (note to self, need to find the photos!).

The setup:¶

The speaker + mics were mounted on tripods at a height of ~1m to avoid ground reflections. The speaker was placed 1.1 meters from the microphone to keep it in the far field, and to be able to recognise any reflections arising from the speaker-mic setup itself.

The playback:¶

The playback was a combination upward frequency sweeps and pure tones. The frequency sweeps were 10 ms long (tukey windowed) between 15-95 kHz. The pure tones were each 100 ms long between 10 to 94 kHz in steps of 1 kHz. Recordings and playback were performed with the Fireface 802. The Channel 9 of the Fireface 802 was used for the input, and channel 1 of the output was used. All playbacks and recordings were performed at 192 kHz sampling rate.

The Vifa speaker was driven by a 12V DC powered car amplifier (BASETECH AP 2100).

The microphones:¶

The same speaker playback was recorded at a variety of angles for each microphone model. There were three microphone models used:

1) SMP Knowles¶

2) SANKEN CO-100¶

3) GRAS 1/4'' calibration microphone¶

The GRAS calibration microphone is a flat frequency response microphone which is used as a reference to compare the frequency response of other microphones. The GRAS mic was used to measure the playback level of the speaker repeatedly over the whole calibration session.

Example upward sweep recorded on GRAS mic¶

Example pure tone playbacks recorded on GRAS mic¶

1) Does the speaker playback vary across time within a calibration session?¶

I've always had the sneaky feeling that speaker playback somehow varies with time - but have never been able to test it. I will now test it by checking the same playback with the GRAS microphone across time.¶

The nice part I realised is that I've used the same gain levels for the same playback file, which means it is straightforward to compare the speaker playback levels by directly comparing the rms of the audio.¶

b,a = signal.butter(4, 8.0/96, 'highpass')

def rms(X):
    sq_X = X**2.0
    mean_sqX = np.mean(sq_X)
    root_meansqX = np.sqrt(mean_sqX)
    return(root_meansqX)

The speaker playback is constant to within 1 dB !¶

Across the ~6 hours that the playback was done over (with gaps etc.) the recorded playback level of the recordings is constant. This is good news as it indicates that I can trust the Vifa speaker to hold a constant level over this time span.¶

Of course, this is a broad picture as I haven't really looked at how each of the playback signals are varying - but for a quick estimate, this already tells me that each of the signals themselves can't have varied too much - otherwise I would've seen more than 1 dB variation in the recorded level.¶

2 How similar are the SMPs to each other?¶

I have SIXTEEN or more SMP mics that contribute to recordings in my dataset at one point or the other. I could do calibration measurements of each of the mics - but this is honestly very time consuming. So far, as of Jan 2019 I mananged to only get done with 10 of them. In general however, I still need to know how different they are from each other...¶

The analysis plan:¶

The essential idea is to again very broadly characterise the on-axis recorded signal levels of each mic. Since I know there is a variation of +/- 1 dB across speaker playbacks, any variation beyond this will indicate microphone individuality.¶

However, here there is a bit complication because each of the mic recordings have different gain settings. I need to account for these gain settings and only then compare the recorded levels across each SMP mic. Having realised that the gain knob markings are not linear, I only used the number of markings from the 30 dB as an indicator.¶

The measured gain values at each knob is the following:¶

Acording to this graph then '2marksfrom30dB' means it is +39 dB gain, and '3marksfrom30dB' means it is +46 dB gain.¶

# highpass at 8 kHz and calculate signal level of the SMP mics:
smps_rec_level = np.zeros(len(all_on_axis_files))
for i, each_file in enumerate(all_on_axis_files):
    smp_rec, fs = sf.read(each_file)
    hp_smp_rec = signal.filtfilt(b,a, smp_rec)

    # get the gain value used:

    # final dBrms :
    final_dBrms = 20*np.log10(rms_smp_rec) - markings_to_dB[gainused]
    smps_rec_level[i] = final_dBrms

3 How similar are the SANKENs to each other?¶

The SANKEN CO-100 is a rather fancy condenser microphone designed for high-end studio use. I have 4 of them with serial numbers 1538, 1539, 1545, 1546 -- which I also have numbered according to the Fireface 802 channel assigned to them: #9,#10,#11,#12. I used the same gain settings on all the mics and so it should again be straightforward to compare them to each other.¶

The effect of continuous usage ... accident to Mic #10 (1539):¶

Once while using the tristar array with all four SANKENs the whole array fell and the protective grill of the SANKEN 1539 took much of the brunt of this fall. I did not notice any dents in the shiny golden membrance below the grill, and the mic registered signal fairly well. The grill looks rather crumpled in comparison to the other SANKEN mics. I've never tried to quantify the effect of this grill crumpling on mic sensitivity till now.¶

The SANKENs show the same effective sensitivity on-axis. Even though SANKEN_10_1539 has a crumpled grill, it is somehow a little bit more sensitive than other mics -- but this is hard to really tease apart given the variation in speaker playback levels <1 dB.¶

Getting received sound pressure levels:¶

Having a GRAS microphone with me, it allows a real-life quantitative measurement of the sound pressure level. Given that we're using the same speaker model for playbacks I must be able to¶

a) calculate the received level with a GRAS microphone¶

b) perform microphone IR/frequency response compensation and calculate received level with other microphones¶

Calculating received levels of the speaker playback with the GRAS mic:¶

We need to first compare the signal from the calibrator tone with the speaker recordings. The calibrator tone is a pute tone at 1 kHz recorded at a received level of 94 dB SPL re 20 $\mu$Pa¶

# load each calibrator tone recording and calculate pp and dB rms:
calibrator_msmts = {'p2p':[],
                    'rms':[],
                    'peak':[]}

for each_rec in gras_calibrator_recs:
    rec_filename = get_filename.search(each_rec).group()
    if rec_filename == remove_wholerec:
        pass
    else:
        audio, fs = sf.read(each_rec)
        
        if rec_filename == remove_firstsecond:
            audio = audio[192000:]

        audio_lp = signal.filtfilt(b_3k, a_3k, audio)
        p2p_val_max,p2p_val_min  = np.percentile(audio_lp,[99,1])
        p2p_val = p2p_val_max - p2p_val_min
        rms_val = rms(audio_lp) # dB re 1 
        peak_val = np.percentile(np.abs(audio_lp),99)# dB re 1 

        calibrator_msmts['p2p'].append(p2p_val)
        calibrator_msmts['rms'].append(rms_val)
        calibrator_msmts['peak'].append(peak_val)

Lesson #1 : Outliers mess with peak and peak-to-peak readings heavily. I was initially unable to obtain the 3dB difference between the rms and peak values of the sinusoidal wave. This was because for whatever reason - there are some strange fluctuations in the recorded calibrator signal - that didn't disappear even after low-pass filtering! When you have even one of them in the recording - they can heavily affect the expected readings becaus they push the averages strongly. I instead now chose to use a percentile approach. Since the sine-waves are regular with very few such weird outlier values, my argument is that it's safer to use the percentiles -- and having implemented it I can now recover the 3 dB relationship!!¶

Multiple 1 kHz calibration tones recorded by GRAS. Box in red shows the unexplained high peak values.¶

The clip level :¶

The clip level of the Fireface 802 is the sound pressure level at which the maximum possible value is reached (+1 or -1). This is calculated by comparing the peak levels of a calibrated tone. Let's do this for our system:¶

The peak level of the calibration tone is : -5 dB peak re 1¶

The calibration tone is a signal produced with 94 dB SPL re 20 $\mu$Pa, and was recorded with 70 dB gain. This means that the actual signal level was -75 dB re 1. This in turn means that the original clip level of the recording system is 94 + 75 = 169 dB peak SPL¶

Similarly for the rms level , it was -8 dB rms re 1. The original signal was thus recorded at -78 dB rms.¶

The clip rms level of the system is thus 94 + 78 = 172 dB rms SPL¶

The received level of the speaker playbacks:¶

Let's try to calculate the received level of the speaker playbacks with the GRAS microphone first.¶

# highpass filter at 8k and calculate peak and rms 
def calc_sweep_params(rec_sweep):
    b,a = signal.butter(2, 8000/96000.0, 'highpass')
    hp_sweep = signal.filtfilt(b,a, rec_sweep)
    peak_val = np.max(np.abs(hp_sweep))
    rms_val = rms(hp_sweep)
    return(peak_val, rms_val)

Some details in the implementation :¶

As usual something has gone unnoticed during the playback recordings itself. The recordings only happened till 92 kHz !! Of course in the actual calibration details it doesn't matter so much, because I'm losing the upper ~3 kHz that are close to the Nyquist frequency anyway. The reason this happened was because of the large buffer size I used and the delay in playback+recording.¶

Let's now compare the actual power at each frequency between 10 - 94 kHz. Because I'm taking the whole recording as such, it will also mean I'm taking the linear sweep into account too - but I think it shouldn't make such a big difference overall.¶

In [45]:
def generate_calibration_playback_sequence():
    '''Code copied from the microphone_calib_playbacks script
    '''
    
    fs = 192000

    # define a common pl.ayback sounds length:
    common_length = 0.7
    numsamples_comlength = int(fs*common_length)

    # Create the calibration chirp : 
    chirp_durn = 0.010
    t_chirp = np.linspace(0,chirp_durn, int(fs*chirp_durn))
    start_f, end_f = 15000, 95000
    sweep = signal.chirp(t_chirp,start_f, t_chirp[-1], end_f, 'linear')
    sweep *= signal.tukey(sweep.size, 0.9)
    sweep *= 0.5

    silence_durn = 0.3
    silence_samples = int(silence_durn*fs)
    silence = np.zeros(silence_samples)
    # create 5 sweeps with silences before & after them :
    sweep_w_leftsilence = np.concatenate((silence,sweep))
    numsamples_to_add = numsamples_comlength - sweep_w_leftsilence.size
    sweep_w_silences = np.concatenate((sweep_w_leftsilence,np.zeros(numsamples_to_add)))
    sweep_w_silences = np.float32(sweep_w_silences)

    all_sweeps = []
    #make a set of 5 sweeps in a row =
    for i in range(5):
        all_sweeps.append(sweep_w_silences)

    # create a set of sinusoidal pulses :
    pulse_durn = 0.1
    pulse_samples = int(fs*pulse_durn)
    t_pulse = np.linspace(0,pulse_durn, pulse_samples)
    pulse_start_f, pulse_end_f  = 10000, 95000
    frequency_step = 1000;
    freqs = np.arange(pulse_start_f, pulse_end_f, frequency_step)

    all_freq_pulses = []
    i = 0 
    for each_freq in freqs:
        one_tone = np.sin(2*np.pi*t_pulse*each_freq)
        one_tone *= signal.tukey(one_tone.size, 0.85)

        if each_freq >=80000:
            one_tone *= 0.75
        else:
            one_tone *= 0.5
        one_tone_w_silences = np.float32(np.concatenate((silence,one_tone,silence)))
        all_freq_pulses.append(one_tone_w_silences)

    # setup the speaker playbacks to first play the sweeps and then 
    # the pulses : 
    playback_sounds = [all_sweeps, all_freq_pulses]
    return(playback_sounds)

all_smp8_msmts = {}

for freq, snippet in sorted(all_smp_snippets.iteritems()):
    
    if not isinstance(freq, str):
        all_smp8_msmts[freq] = {}
        # bandpass to 2  kHz of target frequency
        b,a = signal.butter(2, np.array([freq-2000, freq+2000])/(fs*0.5), 'bandpass')
        bp_snippet = signal.filtfilt(b,a,snippet)
        all_smp8_msmts[freq]['bp_snippet'] = bp_snippet

        # separate tone from background silence and calculate SNR, rms, peak values
        tone = bp_snippet[int(0.3*fs):int(0.4*fs)]
        none_tone = np.concatenate((bp_snippet[:int(0.3*fs)],bp_snippet[int(0.4*fs):]))

        rms_signal = rms(tone)
        all_smp8_msmts[freq]['dB_rms'] = 20*np.log10(rms_signal)
        all_smp8_msmts[freq]['dB_peak'] = 20*np.log10(np.percentile(abs(tone),99))
        rms_noise = rms(none_tone)
        dB_SNR = 20*np.log10(rms_signal/rms_noise)
        all_smp8_msmts[freq]['dB_SNR'] = dB_SNR
